<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: OAK PARK; 
</P>
<P>
SCHOOLS WEIGH Y'S CHILD-CARE PROPOSAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KAREN McKEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Oak Park Unified School District is studying a proposal from the Triunfo 
YMCA to provide preschool and after-school child care for students in the 
Agoura area. 
</P>
<P>
Officials from the YMCA, which covers Westlake Village, Agoura and Oak Park, 
presented the child-care proposal to the school district's Board of Trustees 
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
YMCA Executive Director Pete Regli said his organization would put a portable 
building behind the school district office on Conifer Street and would offer 
various programs at a cost comparable to other preschool and child-care 
programs. Regli said the program would offer sliding-scale payments to 
low-income parents. 
</P>
<P>
The YMCA has not figured out how to come up with the initial financing for the 
preschool, Regli said. 
</P>
<P>
"There is an up-front cost of about $40,000 that we can't afford right now," he 
said. "But the ongoing costs would be paid by the people who use the center." 
</P>
<P>
The preliminary plan is to open a preschool, then expand to after-school child 
care, Regli said. 
</P>
<P>
"We do get a lot of calls from people asking for preschool and child-care 
programs," he said. "We have a problem referring them because there just aren't 
that many preschools." 
</P>
<P>
The proposal was generally well-received by the trustees, who asked Regli to 
return when he has firmer cost estimates and a more detailed plan for programs 
that would be offer. 
</P>
<P>
The school district has 1,580 students at two elementary schools, a middle 
school and a high school. KAREN McKEAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
