<HEADLINE>
<P>
WESTSIDE DIGEST: WEST LOS ANGELES; 
</P>
<P>
YAROSLAVSKY IN MOSCOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky is in the Soviet Union this week to 
meet with government officials, Jewish leaders and representatives of the U.S. 
Embassy, his office said. 
</P>
<P>
Yaroslavsky will be in Moscow until Sunday at the invitation of Dr. Mikhail 
Chlenov, president of Vaad, an association of 210 Jewish organizations. 
</P>
<P>
The Westside councilman's office said the trip was prompted by concerns raised 
when Pamyat, a right-wing nationalistic Soviet organization, urged that 
organized acts of violence be committed Saturday against Jews in Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
Yaroslavsky is accompanied by Si Frumkin, chairman of the Southern California 
Council for Soviet Jews, which is paying for Yaroslavsky's trip, Yaroslavsky 
spokeswoman Katharine Macdonald said. 
</P>
<P>
Before his election to the City Council in 1975, Yaroslavsky served as 
executive director of the group, Macdonald said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
