<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
QANTAS TO PUT EMPHASIS ON ASIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Australia's national airline Qantas today said it will drop four unprofitable 
routes later this year to focus on Asia, which the carrier believes will become 
a major source of tourists for the country. 
</P>
<P>
"We are taking our resources from one part of the planet and putting them in 
another, much more profitable part of the planet," Rodger Robertson, director 
of corporate planning for Qantas, told Reuters. 
</P>
<P>
By this fall, Qantas plans to stop flying to Amsterdam, Athens, Bombay and 
Bahrain. 
</P>
<P>
"These places are losing us money, and there's very little prospect of them 
becoming profitable," Robertson said. 
</P>
