<HEADLINE>
<P>
'GOODBY, DAHLING,' DREYER'S ICE CREAM INFORMS ZSA ZSA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OAKLAND 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream today said ta-ta to Zsa Zsa Gabor, disclosing that it 
has discontinued airing a commercial featuring the actress who slapped the 
Beverly Hills cop. 
</P>
<P>
The ad, which bills Gabor as an "Unbelievable Spokesperson for an Unbelievable 
Product," was one of a series of new commercials for the company's Dreyer's 
Grand Light product. 
</P>
<P>
"The ad campaign features spokespersons known for their 'unbelievable' 
experiences or reputations promoting our 'unbelievably' good product,' " said 
Steven Schickler, vice president of marketing for Dreyer's. 
</P>
<P>
Schickler said that although Gabor's spot was meant to be humorous, Dreyer had 
received more than 300 complaints since announcing that the actress would film 
a commercial for the company. The ad began airing in Dreyer's major markets 
three weeks ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
